ost_step.1: Let $r$ represent the unknown radius of the base of the tank and let $h=4$ m be the height increase each hour since it fills up consistently every hour.
ost_step.2: Volume flow into the open top end varies directly as area times speed; therefore,$V=(BaseArea)(speed)$, so $$RateofVolumeIncoming =\pi r^{2}\cdot h$$where Base Area=$πr²$, Height Rise ($∆h$) = $4\,m/hr$ , Hourly volume added=$20\pi\,m³/(hr)$. Solving yields $$\begin{aligned} V&=\text{rate }\times \text{time}\\ &=(\pi r^2)\left({4 \, m \over hr}\right)(1\,hr)\\ &=\pi r^2(4)\,m\\ & =20\,\pi\,m^3 \\ \Rightarrow &\pi r^2(4)=\pi\,dv\\ \Rightarrow&\quad r^2=\dfrac{20\,m^3}{4}=5\,m^2\\ \therefore\; r&=\sqrt{5}\,m . \end{aligned}$$Thus, the value of our question would yield $radius=5^{\frac {1}{2}}.$ Our required Radius becomes$\sqrt{5}$ meter or left box could read simply '**radian square root five**'.
